photo.title: Bookplate of Edward Heron-Allen (1861-1943)
photo.description: Bookplate of Edward Heron-Allen (1861-1943) Established heading: Heron-Allen, Edward, 1861-1943 The bookplate of Edward Heron-Allen (17 December 1861 – 28 March 1943), a writer, scientist, and Persian scholar, who produced a literal translation of the Quatrians of Omar Khayyam from the earliest known manuscript, which was in the Bodelian Library of Oxford University [1]. Another biographical sketch of him can be found on website maintained by the Heron-Allen Society [2]. The design elements of the bookplate illustrate a number of his interests. He was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society in May 1919 for his work in studying the Foraminifera, a class of microscopic amoeboid protists that produce their own shells, sometime with multiple chambers. Hence, the owl (symbol of learning), the microscope, and flanking his name, two examples of Foraminifera (compare to the samples in this photograph). He was an expert in the art of palmistry, and wrote several books on the subject, hence the palms at 9 and 3 o'clock of the circular device. As a young man, he learned the art of violin-making, and wrote a book on that topic, as well, hence the violin in the foreground. He was a scholar of Persian and translated the works of Omar Khayyam, and so Persian written in Arabic script appears in the bookplate, as well. He is also known as the author (under the pseudonym of Christopher Blayre) of The Cheetah Girl, a book that was suppressed because it dealt with themes of unconventional sexuality. Perhaps that is why a naked woman is being contemplated by the man in Persian garb. Given the fact that he wrote numerous books, he is found in VIAF. photo.description: Ms. inscription: "HS = Hans Schaufelein [...] vid. pag. LIX" The inscription refers to the creator of the woodcut on p. LIX, Hans Leonhard Schäufelein, whose signature often combined a shovel with his monogram. Hans Leonhard Schäufelein (ca. 1480-ca. 1539), a German painter, designer, and wood engraver. From about 1503 he was in Albrecht Dürer's Nuremberg workshop, entrusted with painting important projects during the master's long absences. A highly prolific printmaker, Schäufelein made most of the 150 woodcuts for a 1507 collection of New Testament passages and texts. photo.title: Ms. ownership inscription of Gottlieb Paul Christ (1707-1786)
photo.description: Ms. ownership inscription of Gottlieb Paul Christ (1707-1786): "Theophili Pauli Christii Coburgensis Onoldibati[?] a C.N. MDCCLX." [Gottlieb Paul Christ (1707-1786), professor, librarian and court functionary at Ansbach. In their finding aid Aldine Press Books at the Harry Ransom Humanities Research Center, The University of Texas at Austin (Austin: The Center, 1998), Craig W. Kallendorf and Maria X. Wells identify the ex-libris "Theophili Pauli Christi" as "Gottlieb Paul Christ (18th cent.), prof. at Anspach Gymnasium". According to his biographical entry in C.A. Baader, Lexikon Verstorbener Schrifsteller des 18. und 19. Jahrhunderts (Augsburg: Von Jenisch- und Stage'schen Buchhandlung, 1825), Bd. 2, T. 1, p. 22, Christ was born in Coburg but came to Ansbach in 1728 to take service with Freiherr von Seckendorff (probably Christoph Ludwig Freiherr von Seckendorff-Aberdar). He went abroad on several diplomatic missions and became the librarian for the Ansbacher Schlossbibliothek. (According to E.F.C. Oertel in Georg Ludwig Oeder der erste Rektor bei der Einweihung des neuen Gymnasiums in Ansbach am 12. Juni 1737 ... (Ansbach: Oertel, 1837) p. 54-55, he got the job in 1738; according to the Schlossbibliothek's history web page, he was the second librarian to be appointed.) In 1737 he was appointed professor at the gymnasium in Ansbach and published a number of works on historical subjects; he also continued to serve at court as a councillor. DNB heading: Christ, Gottlieb Paul 1707-1786] Other examples of Gottlieb Paul Christ provenance Penn Libraries call number: LatC P7198 En543n Folio All images from this book

photo.title: Inscription by the author, William Smith (1727-1803), to John Morgan (1735-1789)
photo.description: Inscription by the author, William Smith to John Morgan, who is one of the graduates listed in a ms. list of "The names of the gentlemen, on whom degrees were conferr'd at that commencement, & to whom the charge was delivered ..." on the blank page [128] preceding Appendix no. III, "A charge delivered to the graduates at the first anniversary commencement in the College of Philadelphia." The list was written either by the author, William Smith, or by the owner of the book, John Morgan. William Smith (1727-1803) was provost of the College of Philadelphia, 1755-1779 and 1789-1791 and was orrdained as a clergyman in the Church of England in 1754. His papers are held by the Penn Libraries (catalog record). John Morgan was an alumnus of the College of Philadelphia (A.B., 1757) and the University of Edinburgh (M.D., 1763). He traveled in Europe before returning to Philadelphia and founding the first medical school in the American colonies at the College of Philadelphia in 1765. His journal, recording his travels in Europe, is held by the Penn Libraries (catalog record). Established heading: Smith, William, 1727-1803 Established heading: Morgan, John, 1735-1789 Penn Libraries call number: AC7 Sm683 759db copy 2 All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record
